<DOC><DOCNO> AP880314-0291 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-88 0732EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   03-14 0448</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0468</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The head of the Inter-American DevelopmentBank says its loans to Latin America will increase from last year's$2.36 billion to between $2.5 billion and $3 billion in 1988.   ``We can continue on this level until the end of the century,''Antonio Ortiz Mena, the departing president, told a news conferenceFriday.   The bank, owned by 44 governments, is a major source of loans toraise the living standards of Latin American countries.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The First National Bank of Boston has agreed tofreeze activity on Panamanian government accounts until the StateDepartment lifts sanctions against the nation.   The action Friday stems from a civil suit filed earlier thisweek by Panama's U.S. ambassador, Juan B. Sosa, the recognizedrepresentative of the government of deposed President Eric ArturoDelvalle.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prosecutors are portraying two former bankexecutives as greedy men hungry for wealth in a fraud trial linkedto the near-demise of Continental Illinois Bank and Trust Co.   The government has accused former Continental Vice PresidentJohn Lytle of buying high-risk loans from now-defunct Penn SquareBank in Oklahoma City in exchange for kickbacks.   Defendant William Patterson, former head of energy lending atPenn Square, gave the kickbacks to Lytle in the form of unsecuredloans, the government contended in U.S. District Court Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Home Shopping Network Inc., the leader intelevised shop-from-home programs, said telephone problems wereresponsible for a 44 percent decline in second-quarter earnings.   The telephone problems _ since corrected _ prevented somepotential customers from placing orders, and contributed to aninventory buildup that the company is still trying to reduce bycutting prices on some merchandise, Roy Speer, chairman and chiefexecutive of Home Shopping, said Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Kuwait will raise its stake in British PetroleumCo. PLC to 22.5 percent but no more, and will not seekrepresentation on the board of directors, an official of thePersian Gulf nation's investment arm says.   The remarks Friday, by the chief investment manager of theKuwait Investment Office, were the first direct statements ofKuwait's immediate intentions toward BP.   Some analysts suggested Kuwait ultimately wants access to BP'sextensive refining and marketing operations in Europe and theUnited States.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market rallied from behind late Friday. The Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrials, down more than 20 points atmidafternoon, closed with a gain of 8.95 at 2,034.98.   The dollar declined in quiet trading and gold prices slipped.Bonds rose in response to news of low inflation and slow retailsales.   Cotton futures prices jumped.</TEXT></DOC>